# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rheology-materials
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rheology-materials/deborah-number] The **Deborah number** (**De**) is a dimensionless number, often used in rheology to characterize the fluidity of materials under specific flow conditions.
[src:rheology-materials/deborah-number] It quantifies the observation that given enough time even a solid-like material might flow, or a fluid-like material can act solid when it is deformed rapidly enough.
[src:rheology-materials/deborah-number] Materials that have low relaxation times flow easily and as such show relatively rapid stress decay.
[src:rheology-materials/deborah-number] The Deborah number is the ratio of fundamentally different characteristic times.
[src:rheology-materials/deborah-number] where *t*c stands for the relaxation time and *t*p for the "time of observation", typically taken to be the time scale of the process.
[src:rheology-materials/deborah-number] The numerator, relaxation time, is the time needed for a reference amount of deformation to occur under a suddenly applied reference load (a more fluid-like material will therefore require less time to flow, giving a lower Deborah number relative to a solid subjected to the same loading rate).
[src:rheology-materials/deborah-number] The denominator, material time, is the amount of time required to reach a given reference strain (a faster loading rate will therefore reach the reference strain sooner, giving a higher Deborah number).
[src:rheology-materials/deborah-number] Equivalently, the relaxation time is the time required for the stress induced, by a suddenly applied reference strain, to reduce by a certain reference amount.
[src:rheology-materials/deborah-number] The relaxation time is actually based on the rate of relaxation that exists at the moment of the suddenly applied load.
[src:rheology-materials/deborah-number] This incorporates both the elasticity and viscosity of the material.
[src:rheology-materials/deborah-number] At lower Deborah numbers, the material behaves in a more fluidlike manner, with an associated Newtonian viscous flow.
[src:rheology-materials/deborah-number] At higher Deborah numbers, the material behavior enters the non-Newtonian regime, increasingly dominated by elasticity and demonstrating solidlike behavior.
[src:rheology-materials/deborah-number] For example, for a Hookean elastic solid, the relaxation time *t*c will be infinite and it will vanish for a Newtonian viscous fluid.
[src:rheology-materials/deborah-number] For liquid water, *t*c is typically 10−12 s, for lubricating oils passing through gear teeth at high pressure it is of the order of 10−6 s and for polymers undergoing plastics processing, the relaxation time will be of the order of a few seconds.
[src:rheology-materials/deborah-number] Therefore, depending on the situation, these liquids may exhibit elastic properties, departing from purely viscous behavior.
[src:rheology-materials/deborah-number] While De is similar to the Weissenberg number and is often confused with it in technical literature, they have different physical interpretations.
[src:rheology-materials/deborah-number] The Weissenberg number indicates the degree of anisotropy or orientation generated by the deformation, and is appropriate to describe flows with a constant stretch history, such as simple shear.
[src:rheology-materials/deborah-number] In contrast, the Deborah number should be used to describe flows with a non-constant stretch history, and physically represents the rate at which elastic energy is stored or released.
[src:rheology-materials/deborah-number] The Deborah number is particularly useful in conceptualizing the time–temperature superposition principle.
[src:rheology-materials/deborah-number] Time-temperature superposition has to do with altering experimental time scales using reference temperatures to extrapolate temperature-dependent mechanical properties of polymers.
[src:rheology-materials/deborah-number] A material at low temperature with a long experimental or relaxation time behaves like the same material at high temperature and short experimental or relaxation time if the Deborah number remains the same.
[src:rheology-materials/deborah-number] This can be particularly useful when working with materials which relax on a long time scale under a certain temperature.
[src:rheology-materials/deborah-number] The practical application of this idea arises in the Williams–Landel–Ferry equation.
[src:rheology-materials/deborah-number] Time-temperature superposition avoids the inefficiency of measuring a polymer's behavior over long periods of time at a specified temperature by utilizing the Deborah number.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] In physical chemistry and fluid mechanics, a **non-Newtonian fluid** is a fluid that does not follow Newton's law of viscosity; that is, it has variable viscosity dependent on stress.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] In particular, the viscosity of non-Newtonian fluids can change when subjected to force.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Ketchup, for example, becomes runnier when shaken and is thus a non-Newtonian fluid.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Many salt solutions and molten polymers are non-Newtonian fluids, as are many commonly found substances such as custard, toothpaste, starch suspensions, paint, blood, melted butter and shampoo.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Most commonly, the viscosity (the gradual deformation by shear or tensile stresses) of non-Newtonian fluids is dependent on shear rate or shear rate history.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Some non-Newtonian fluids with shear-independent viscosity, however, still exhibit normal stress-differences or other non-Newtonian behavior.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] In a Newtonian fluid, the relation between the shear stress and the shear rate is linear, passing through the origin, the constant of proportionality being the coefficient of viscosity.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] In a non-Newtonian fluid, the relation between the shear stress and the shear rate is different.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] The fluid can even exhibit time-dependent viscosity.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Therefore, a constant coefficient of viscosity cannot be defined.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Although the concept of viscosity is commonly used in fluid mechanics to characterize the shear properties of a fluid, it can be inadequate to describe non-Newtonian fluids.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] They are best studied through several other rheological properties that relate stress and strain rate tensors under many different flow conditions—such as oscillatory shear or extensional flow—which are measured using different devices or rheometers.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] The properties are better studied using tensor-valued constitutive equations, which are common in the field of continuum mechanics.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] For non-Newtonian fluid's viscosity, there are pseudoplastic, plastic, and dilatant flows that are time-independent, and there are thixotropic and rheopectic flows that are time-dependent.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Three well-known time-dependent non-newtonian fluids which can be identified by the defining authors are the Oldroyd-B model, Walters’ Liquid B and Williamson fluids.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Time-dependent self-similar analysis of the Ladyzenskaya-type model with a non-linear velocity dependent stress tensor was performed.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] No analytical solutions could be derived, but a rigorous mathematical existence theorem was given for the solution.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] For time-independent non-Newtonian fluids the known analytic solutions are much broader.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] The viscosity of a shear thickening – i.e. dilatant – fluid appears to increase when the shear rate increases.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Corn starch suspended in water ("oobleck", see below) is a common example: when stirred slowly it looks milky, when stirred vigorously it feels like a very viscous liquid.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] A familiar example of the opposite, a shear thinning fluid, or pseudoplastic fluid, is wall paint: The paint should flow readily off the brush when it is being applied to a surface but not drip excessively.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Note that all thixotropic fluids are extremely shear thinning, but they are significantly time dependent, whereas the colloidal "shear thinning" fluids respond instantaneously to changes in shear rate.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Thus, to avoid confusion, the latter classification is more clearly termed pseudoplastic.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Another example of a shear thinning fluid is blood.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] This application is highly favoured within the body, as it allows the viscosity of blood to decrease with increased shear strain rate.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Fluids that have a linear shear stress/shear strain relationship but require a finite yield stress before they begin to flow (the plot of shear stress against shear strain does not pass through the origin) are called Bingham plastics.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Several examples are clay suspensions, drilling mud, toothpaste, mayonnaise, chocolate, and mustard.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] The surface of a Bingham plastic can hold peaks when it is still.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] By contrast Newtonian fluids have flat featureless surfaces when still.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] There are also fluids whose strain rate is a function of time.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Fluids that require a gradually increasing shear stress to maintain a constant strain rate are referred to as rheopectic.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] An opposite case of this is a fluid that thins out with time and requires a decreasing stress to maintain a constant strain rate (thixotropic).
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Many common substances exhibit non-Newtonian flows.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] An inexpensive, non-toxic example of a non-Newtonian fluid is a suspension of starch (e.g., cornstarch/cornflour) in water, sometimes called "oobleck", "ooze", or "magic mud" (1 part of water to 1.5–2 parts of corn starch).
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] The name "oobleck" is derived from the Dr.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Seuss book *Bartholomew and the Oobleck*.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Because of its dilatant properties, oobleck is often used in demonstrations that exhibit its unusual behavior.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] A person may walk on a large tub of oobleck without sinking due to its shear thickening properties, as long as the individual moves quickly enough to provide enough force with each step to cause the thickening.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Also, if oobleck is placed on a large subwoofer driven at a sufficiently high volume, it will thicken and form standing waves in response to low frequency sound waves from the speaker.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] If a person were to punch or hit oobleck, it would thicken and act like a solid.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] After the blow, the oobleck will go back to its thin liquid-like state.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Flubber, also commonly known as slime, is a non-Newtonian fluid, easily made from polyvinyl acetate–based glues (such as white "school" glue) and borax.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] It flows under low stresses but breaks under higher stresses and pressures.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] This combination of fluid-like and solid-like properties makes it a Maxwell fluid.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Its behaviour can also be described as being viscoplastic or gelatinous.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Another example of non-Newtonian fluid flow is chilled caramel ice cream topping (so long as it incorporates hydrocolloids such as carrageenan and gellan gum).
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] The sudden application of force—by stabbing the surface with a finger, for example, or rapidly inverting the container holding it—causes the fluid to behave like a solid rather than a liquid.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] This is the "shear thickening" property of this non-Newtonian fluid.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Gentler treatment, such as slowly inserting a spoon, will leave it in its liquid state.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Trying to jerk the spoon back out again, however, will trigger the return of the temporary solid state.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Silly Putty is a silicone polymer based suspension that will flow, bounce, or break, depending on strain rate.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Plant resin is a viscoelastic solid polymer.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] When left in a container, it will flow slowly as a liquid to conform to the contours of its container.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] If struck with greater force, however, it will shatter as a solid.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Quicksand is a shear thinning non-Newtonian colloid that gains viscosity at rest.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Quicksand's non-Newtonian properties can be observed when it experiences a slight shock (for example, when someone walks on it or agitates it with a stick), shifting between its gel and sol phase and seemingly liquefying, causing objects on the surface of the quicksand to sink.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Shear thinning means that the fluid viscosity decreases with increasing shear stress.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] In other words, fluid motion is initially difficult at slow rates of deformation, but will flow more freely at high rates.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Shaking an inverted bottle of ketchup can cause it to transition to a lower viscosity through shear thinning, making it easier to pour from the bottle.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Under certain circumstances, flows of granular materials can be modelled as a continuum, for example using the *μ*(*I*) rheology.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] Such continuum models tend to be non-Newtonian, since the apparent viscosity of granular flows increases with pressure and decreases with shear rate.
[src:rheology-materials/non-newtonian-fluid] The main difference is the shearing stress and rate of shear.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] The term *rheology* was coined by Eugene C.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Bingham, a professor at Lafayette College, in 1920 from a suggestion by a colleague, Markus Reiner.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] The term was inspired by the aphorism of Heraclitus (often mistakenly attributed to Simplicius), *panta rhei* (πάντα ῥεῖ, 'everything flows') and was first used to describe the flow of liquids and the deformation of solids.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Newtonian fluids can be characterized by a single coefficient of viscosity for a specific temperature.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Although this viscosity will change with temperature, it does not change with the strain rate.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Only a small group of fluids exhibit such constant viscosity.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] The large class of fluids whose viscosity changes with the strain rate (the relative flow velocity) are called non-Newtonian fluids.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Rheology generally accounts for the behavior of non-Newtonian fluids by characterizing the minimum number of functions that are needed to relate stresses with rate of change of strain or strain rates.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] For example, ketchup can have its viscosity reduced by shaking (or other forms of mechanical agitation, where the relative movement of different layers in the material actually causes the reduction in viscosity), but water cannot.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Ketchup is a shear-thinning material, like yogurt and emulsion paint (US terminology latex paint or acrylic paint), exhibiting thixotropy, where an increase in relative flow velocity will cause a reduction in viscosity, for example, by stirring.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Some other non-Newtonian materials show the opposite behavior, rheopecty (viscosity increasing with relative deformation), and are called shear-thickening or dilatant materials.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Since Sir Isaac Newton originated the concept of viscosity, the study of liquids with strain-rate-dependent viscosity is also often called non-Newtonian fluid mechanics.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] The experimental characterisation of a material's rheological behaviour is known as *rheometry*, although the term *rheology* is frequently used synonymously with rheometry, particularly by experimentalists.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Theoretical aspects of rheology are the relation of the flow/deformation behaviour of material and its internal structure (e.g., the orientation and elongation of polymer molecules) and the flow/deformation behaviour of materials that cannot be described by classical fluid mechanics or elasticity.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] In practice, rheology is principally concerned with extending continuum mechanics to characterize the flow of materials that exhibit a combination of elastic, viscous and plastic behavior by properly combining elasticity and (Newtonian) fluid mechanics.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] It is also concerned with predicting mechanical behavior (on the continuum mechanical scale) based on the micro- or nanostructure of the material, e.g. the molecular size and architecture of polymers in solution or the particle size distribution in a solid suspension.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Materials with the characteristics of a fluid will flow when subjected to a stress, which is defined as the force per area.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] There are different sorts of stress (e.g. shear, torsional, etc.), and materials can respond differently under different stresses.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Much of theoretical rheology is concerned with associating external forces and torques with internal stresses, internal strain gradients, and flow velocities.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Rheology unites the seemingly unrelated fields of plasticity and non-Newtonian fluid dynamics by recognizing that materials undergoing these types of deformation are unable to support a stress (particularly a shear stress, since it is easier to analyze shear deformation) in static equilibrium.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] In this sense, a solid undergoing plastic deformation is a fluid, although no viscosity coefficient is associated with this flow.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Granular rheology refers to the continuum mechanical description of granular materials.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] One of the major tasks of rheology is to establish by measurement the relationships between strains (or rates of strain) and stresses, although a number of theoretical developments (such as assuring frame invariants) are also required before using the empirical data.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] These experimental techniques are known as rheometry and are concerned with the determination of well-defined *rheological material functions*.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Such relationships are then amenable to mathematical treatment by the established methods of continuum mechanics.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] The characterization of flow or deformation originating from a simple shear stress field is called **shear rheometry** (or shear rheology).
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] The study of extensional flows is called **extensional rheology**.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Shear flows are much easier to study and thus much more experimental data are available for shear flows than for extensional flows.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] On one end of the spectrum we have an inviscid or a simple Newtonian fluid and on the other end, a rigid solid; thus the behavior of all materials fall somewhere in between these two ends.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] The difference in material behavior is characterized by the level and nature of elasticity present in the material when it deforms, which takes the material behavior to the non-Newtonian regime.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] The non-dimensional Deborah number is designed to account for the degree of non-Newtonian behavior in a flow.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] The Deborah number is defined as the ratio of the characteristic time of relaxation (which purely depends on the material and other conditions like the temperature) to the characteristic time of experiment or observation.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Small Deborah numbers represent Newtonian flow, while non-Newtonian (with both viscous and elastic effects present) behavior occurs for intermediate range Deborah numbers, and high Deborah numbers indicate an elastic/rigid solid.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Since Deborah number is a relative quantity, the numerator or the denominator can alter the number.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] A very small Deborah number can be obtained for a fluid with extremely small relaxation time or a very large experimental time, for example.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] In fluid mechanics, the Reynolds number is a measure of the ratio of inertial forces ( $v_{s}\rho$ ) to viscous forces ( ${\frac {\mu }{L}}$ ) and consequently it quantifies the relative importance of these two types of effect for given flow conditions.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Under low Reynolds numbers viscous effects dominate and the flow is laminar, whereas at high Reynolds numbers inertia predominates and the flow may be turbulent.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] However, since rheology is concerned with fluids which do not have a fixed viscosity, but one which can vary with flow and time, calculation of the Reynolds number can be complicated.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] It is one of the most important dimensionless numbers in fluid dynamics and is used, usually along with other dimensionless numbers, to provide a criterion for determining dynamic similitude.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] When two geometrically similar flow patterns, in perhaps different fluids with possibly different flow rates, have the same values for the relevant dimensionless numbers, they are said to be dynamically similar.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Rheometers are instruments used to characterize the rheological properties of materials, typically fluids that are melts or solution.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] These instruments impose a specific stress field or deformation to the fluid, and monitor the resultant deformation or stress.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Instruments can be run in steady flow or oscillatory flow, in both shear and extension.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Rheology has applications in materials science, engineering, geophysics, physiology, human biology and pharmaceutics.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Materials science is utilized in the production of many industrially important substances, such as cement, paint, and chocolate, which have complex flow characteristics.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] In addition, plasticity theory has been similarly important for the design of metal forming processes.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] The science of rheology and the characterization of viscoelastic properties in the production and use of polymeric materials has been critical for the production of many products for use in both the industrial and military sectors.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Study of flow properties of liquids is important for pharmacists working in the manufacture of several dosage forms, such as simple liquids, ointments, creams, pastes etc.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] The flow behavior of liquids under applied stress is of great relevance in the field of pharmacy.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Flow properties are used as important quality control tools to maintain the superiority of the product and reduce batch to batch variations.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Examples may be given to illustrate the potential applications of these principles to practical problems in the processing and use of rubbers, plastics, and fibers.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Polymers constitute the basic materials of the rubber and plastic industries and are of vital importance to the textile, petroleum, automobile, paper, and pharmaceutical industries.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Their viscoelastic properties determine the mechanical performance of the final products of these industries, and also the success of processing methods at intermediate stages of production.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] In viscoelastic materials, such as most polymers and plastics, the presence of liquid-like behaviour depends on the properties of and so varies with rate of applied load, i.e., how quickly a force is applied.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] The silicone toy 'Silly Putty' behaves quite differently depending on the time rate of applying a force.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Pull on it slowly and it exhibits continuous flow, similar to that evidenced in a highly viscous liquid.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Alternatively, when hit hard and directly, it shatters like a silicate glass.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] In addition, conventional rubber undergoes a glass transition (often called a *rubber-glass transition*).
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] The Space Shuttle *Challenger* disaster was caused by rubber O-rings that were being used well below their glass transition temperature on an unusually cold Florida morning, and thus could not flex adequately to form proper seals between sections of the two solid-fuel rocket boosters.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] With the viscosity of a sol adjusted into a proper range, both optical quality glass fiber and refractory ceramic fiber can be drawn which are used for fiber-optic sensors and thermal insulation, respectively.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] The mechanisms of hydrolysis and condensation, and the rheological factors that bias the structure toward linear or branched structures are the most critical issues of sol-gel science and technology.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] The scientific discipline of geophysics includes study of the flow of molten lava and study of debris flows (fluid mudslides).
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] This disciplinary branch also deals with solid Earth materials which only exhibit flow over extended time-scales.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Those that display viscous behaviour are known as rheids.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] For example, granite can flow plastically with a negligible yield stress at room temperatures (i.e. a viscous flow).
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Long-term creep experiments (~10 years) indicate that the viscosity of granite and glass under ambient conditions are on the order of 1020 poises.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Physiology includes the study of many bodily fluids that have complex structure and composition, and thus exhibit a wide range of viscoelastic flow characteristics.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] In particular there is a specialist study of blood flow called hemorheology.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] This is the study of flow properties of blood and its elements (plasma and formed elements, including red blood cells, white blood cells and platelets).
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Blood viscosity is determined by plasma viscosity, hematocrit (volume fraction of red blood cell, which constitute 99.9% of the cellular elements) and mechanical behaviour of red blood cells.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] The leading characteristic for hemorheology has been shear thinning in steady shear flow.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Other non-Newtonian rheological characteristics that blood can demonstrate includes pseudoplasticity, viscoelasticity, and thixotropy.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] There are two current major hypotheses to explain blood flow predictions and shear thinning responses.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] The two models also attempt to demonstrate the drive for reversible red blood cell aggregation, although the mechanism is still being debated.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] There is a direct effect of red blood cell aggregation on blood viscosity and circulation.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] The foundation of hemorheology can also provide information for modeling of other biofluids.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] The bridging or "cross-bridging" hypothesis suggests that macromolecules physically crosslink adjacent red blood cells into rouleaux structures.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] This occurs through adsorption of macromolecules onto the red blood cell surfaces.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] The depletion layer hypothesis suggests the opposite mechanism.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] The surfaces of the red blood cells are bound together by an osmotic pressure gradient that is created by depletion layers overlapping.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] The effect of rouleaux aggregation tendency can be explained by hematocrit and fibrinogen concentration in whole blood rheology.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Some techniques researchers use are optical trapping and microfluidics to measure cell interaction in vitro.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Changes to viscosity has been shown to be linked with diseases like hyperviscosity, hypertension, sickle cell anemia, and diabetes.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Hemorheological measurements and genomic testing technologies act as preventative measures and diagnostic tools.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Hemorheology has also been correlated with aging effects, especially with impaired blood fluidity, and studies have shown that physical activity may improve the thickening of blood rheology.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Many animals make use of rheological phenomena, for example sandfish that exploit the granular rheology of dry sand to "swim" in it or land gastropods that use snail slime for adhesive locomotion.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Certain animals produce specialized endogenous complex fluids, such as the sticky slime produced by velvet worms to immobilize prey or the fast-gelling underwater slime secreted by hagfish to deter predators.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Food rheology is important in the manufacture and processing of food products, such as cheese and gelato.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] An adequate rheology is important for the indulgence of many common foods, particularly in the case of sauces, dressings, yogurt, or fondue.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Thickening agents, or thickeners, are substances which, when added to an aqueous mixture, increase its viscosity without substantially modifying its other properties, such as taste.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] They provide body, increase stability, and improve suspension of added ingredients.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Thickening agents are often used as food additives and in cosmetics and personal hygiene products.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Some thickening agents are **gelling agents**, forming a gel.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] The agents are materials used to thicken and stabilize liquid solutions, emulsions, and suspensions.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] They dissolve in the liquid phase as a colloid mixture that forms a weakly cohesive internal structure.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Food thickeners frequently are based on either polysaccharides (starches, vegetable gums, and pectin), or proteins.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Concrete's and mortar's workability is related to the rheological properties of the fresh cement paste.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] The mechanical properties of hardened concrete increase if less water is used in the concrete mix design, however reducing the water-to-cement ratio may decrease the ease of mixing and application.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] To avoid these undesired effects, superplasticizers are typically added to decrease the apparent yield stress and the viscosity of the fresh paste.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Their addition highly improves concrete and mortar properties.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] The incorporation of various types of fillers into polymers is a common means of reducing cost and to impart certain desirable mechanical, thermal, electrical and magnetic properties to the resulting material.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] The advantages that filled polymer systems have to offer come with an increased complexity in the rheological behavior.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] The rheological properties of filled polymers are determined not only by the type and amount of filler, but also by the shape, size and size distribution of its particles.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] The viscosity of filled systems generally increases with increasing filler fraction.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] This can be partially ameliorated via broad particle size distributions via the Farris effect.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] An additional factor is the stress transfer at the filler-polymer interface.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] The interfacial adhesion can be substantially enhanced via a coupling agent that adheres well to both the polymer and the filler particles.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] The type and amount of surface treatment on the filler are thus additional parameters affecting the rheological and material properties of filled polymeric systems.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] It is important to take into consideration wall slip when performing the rheological characterization of highly filled materials, as there can be a large difference between the actual strain and the measured strain.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] A rheologist is an interdisciplinary scientist or engineer who studies the flow of complex liquids or the deformation of soft solids.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] It is not a primary degree subject; there is no qualification of rheologist as such.
[src:rheology-materials/rheology] Typically, a small amount of rheology may be studied when obtaining a degree, but a person working in rheology will extend this knowledge during postgraduate research or by attending short courses and by joining a professional association.
[src:rheology-materials/shear-stress] The formula to calculate average shear stress τ or force per unit area is $\tau ={F \over A},$ where F is the force applied and A is the cross-sectional area.
[src:rheology-materials/shear-stress] It is used, for example, in the description of arterial blood flow, where there is evidence that it affects the atherogenic process.
[src:rheology-materials/shear-stress] Pure shear stress is related to pure shear strain, denoted γ, by the equation $\tau =\gamma G,$ where G is the shear modulus of the isotropic material, given by $G={\frac {E}{2(1+\nu )}}.$ Here, E is Young's modulus and ν is Poisson's ratio.
[src:rheology-materials/shear-stress] The beam shear formula is also known as Zhuravskii shear stress formula after Dmitrii Ivanovich Zhuravskii, who derived it in 1855.
[src:rheology-materials/shear-stress] Shear stresses within a semi-monocoque structure may be calculated by idealizing the cross-section of the structure into a set of stringers (carrying only axial loads) and webs (carrying only shear flows).
[src:rheology-materials/shear-stress] Dividing the shear flow by the thickness of a given portion of the semi-monocoque structure yields the shear stress.
[src:rheology-materials/shear-stress] Thus, the maximum shear stress will occur either in the web of maximum shear flow or minimum thickness.
[src:rheology-materials/shear-stress] Constructions in soil can also fail due to shear; e.g., the weight of an earth-filled dam or dike may cause the subsoil to collapse, like a small landslide.
[src:rheology-materials/shear-stress] Any real fluids (liquids and gases included) moving along a solid boundary will incur a shear stress at that boundary.
[src:rheology-materials/shear-stress] The no-slip condition dictates that the speed of the fluid at the boundary (relative to the boundary) is zero, although at some height from the boundary, the flow speed must equal that of the fluid.
[src:rheology-materials/shear-stress] The region between these two points is named the boundary layer.
[src:rheology-materials/shear-stress] For all Newtonian fluids in laminar flow, the shear stress is proportional to the strain rate in the fluid, where the viscosity is the constant of proportionality.
[src:rheology-materials/shear-stress] For non-Newtonian fluids, the viscosity is not constant.
[src:rheology-materials/shear-stress] The shear stress is imparted onto the boundary as a result of this loss of velocity.
[src:rheology-materials/shear-stress] For an isotropic Newtonian flow, it is a scalar, while for anisotropic Newtonian flows, it can be a second-order tensor.
[src:rheology-materials/shear-stress] On the other hand, given a shear stress as function of the flow velocity, it represents a Newtonian flow only if it can be expressed as a constant for the gradient of the flow velocity.
[src:rheology-materials/shear-stress] The constant one finds in this case is the dynamic viscosity of the flow.
[src:rheology-materials/shear-stress] This relationship can be exploited to measure the wall shear stress.
[src:rheology-materials/shear-stress] If a sensor could directly measure the gradient of the velocity profile at the wall, then multiplying by the dynamic viscosity would yield the shear stress.
[src:rheology-materials/shear-stress] The interference pattern generated by sending a beam of light through two parallel slits forms a network of linearly diverging fringes that seem to originate from the plane of the two slits (see double-slit experiment).
[src:rheology-materials/shear-stress] As a particle in a fluid passes through the fringes, a receiver detects the reflection of the fringe pattern.
[src:rheology-materials/shear-stress] The signal can be processed, and from the fringe angle, the height and velocity of the particle can be extrapolated.
[src:rheology-materials/shear-stress] The measured value of the wall velocity gradient is independent of the fluid properties, and as a result does not require calibration.
[src:rheology-materials/shear-stress] Recent advancements in the micro-optic fabrication technologies have made it possible to use integrated diffractive optical elements to fabricate diverging fringe shear stress sensors usable both in air and liquid.
[src:rheology-materials/shear-stress] A further measurement technique is that of slender wall-mounted micro-pillars made of the flexible polymer polydimethylsiloxane, which bend in reaction to the applying drag forces in the vicinity of the wall.
[src:rheology-materials/shear-stress] The sensor thereby belongs to the indirect measurement principles relying on the relationship between near-wall velocity gradients and the local wall-shear stress.
[src:rheology-materials/shear-stress] The electro-diffusional method measures the wall shear rate in the liquid phase from microelectrodes under limiting diffusion current conditions.
[src:rheology-materials/shear-stress] A potential difference between an anode of a broad surface (usually located far from the measuring area) and the small working electrode acting as a cathode leads to a fast redox reaction.
[src:rheology-materials/shear-stress] The ion disappearance occurs only on the microprobe active surface, causing the development of the diffusion boundary layer, in which the fast electro-diffusion reaction rate is controlled only by diffusion.
[src:rheology-materials/shear-stress] The resolution of the convective-diffusive equation in the near-wall region of the microelectrode lead to analytical solutions relying the characteristics length of the microprobes, the diffusional properties of the electrochemical solution, and the wall shear rate.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] A viscoelastic material shows elastic properties on short time scales and viscous properties on long time scales.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] These materials exhibit behavior that depends on the time and rate of applied forces, allowing them to both store and dissipate energy.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Viscoelasticity has been studied since the 19th century by researchers such as James Clerk Maxwell, Ludwig Boltzmann, and Lord Kelvin.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The viscoelastic properties of polymers are highly temperature dependent.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] From low to high temperature the material can be in the glass phase, rubber phase or the melt phase.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] These phases have a very strong effect on the mechanical and viscous properties of the polymers.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The viscoelasticity properties are measured with various techniques, such as tensile testing, dynamic mechanical analysis, shear rheometry and extensional rheometry.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] In the nineteenth century, physicists such as James Clerk Maxwell, Ludwig Boltzmann, and Lord Kelvin researched and experimented with creep and recovery of glasses, metals, and rubbers.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Viscoelasticity was further examined in the late twentieth century when synthetic polymers were engineered and used in a variety of applications.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Viscoelasticity calculations depend heavily on the viscosity variable, *η*.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The inverse of *η* is also known as fluidity, *φ*.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The value of either can be derived as a function of temperature or as a given value (i.e. for a dashpot).
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Some examples of viscoelastic materials are amorphous polymers, semicrystalline polymers, biopolymers, metals at very high temperatures, and bitumen materials.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Cracking occurs when the strain is applied quickly and outside of the elastic limit.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Ligaments and tendons in the human body are viscoelastic, so the extent of the potential damage to them depends on both the rate of the change of their length and the force applied.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Unlike purely elastic substances, a viscoelastic substance has an elastic component and a viscous component.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The viscosity of a viscoelastic substance gives the substance a strain rate dependence on time.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Purely elastic materials do not dissipate energy (heat) when a load is applied, then removed.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] However, a viscoelastic substance dissipates energy when a load is applied, then removed.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Hysteresis is observed in the stress–strain curve, with the area of the loop being equal to the energy lost during the loading cycle.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Since viscosity is the resistance to thermally activated plastic deformation, a viscous material loses energy through a loading cycle.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Plastic deformation results in lost energy, which is uncharacteristic of a purely elastic material's reaction to a loading cycle.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Specifically, viscoelasticity is a molecular rearrangement.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] When a stress is applied to a viscoelastic material such as a polymer, parts of the long polymer chain change positions.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] This movement or rearrangement is called creep.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Polymers remain a solid material even when these parts of their chains are rearranging to accommodate the stress, and as this occurs, it creates a back stress in the material.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] When the back stress is the same magnitude as the applied stress, the material no longer creeps.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] When the original stress is taken away, the accumulated back stresses causes the polymer to return to its original form.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The material creeps, which gives the prefix visco-, and the material fully recovers, which gives the suffix -elasticity.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Linear viscoelasticity is usually applicable only for small deformations.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] In **nonlinear viscoelasticity**, the function is not separable.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] It usually happens when the deformations are large or if the material changes its properties under deformations.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Nonlinear viscoelasticity also elucidates observed phenomena such as normal stresses, shear thinning, and extensional thickening in viscoelastic fluids.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] An **anelastic** material is a special case of a viscoelastic material: an anelastic material fully recovers to its original state on the removal of load.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Viscoelasticity is studied using dynamic mechanical analysis, applying a small oscillatory stress and measuring the resulting strain.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Viscoelastic materials, such as amorphous polymers, semicrystalline polymers, biopolymers and even the living tissue and cells, can be modeled in order to determine their stress and strain or force and displacement interactions as well as their temporal dependencies.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] These models, which include the Maxwell model, the Kelvin–Voigt model, the standard linear solid model, and the Burgers model, are used to predict a material's response under different loading conditions.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Viscoelastic behavior has elastic and viscous components modeled as linear combinations of springs and dashpots, respectively.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Each model differs in the arrangement of these elements, and all of these viscoelastic models can be equivalently modeled as electrical circuits.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] In an equivalent electrical circuit, stress is represented by current, and strain rate by voltage.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The elastic modulus of a spring is analogous to the inverse of a circuit's *inductance* (it stores energy) and the viscosity of a dashpot to a circuit's *resistance* (it dissipates energy).
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The elastic components, as previously mentioned, can be modeled as springs of elastic constant E, given the formula: $\sigma =E\varepsilon$ where σ is the stress, E is the elastic modulus of the material, and ε is the strain that occurs under the given stress, similar to Hooke's law.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The viscous components can be modeled as dashpots such that the stress–strain rate relationship can be given as, $\sigma =\eta {\frac {d\varepsilon }{dt}}$ where σ is the stress, η is the viscosity of the material, and dε/dt is the time derivative of strain.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The relationship between stress and strain can be simplified for specific stress or strain rates.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] For high stress or strain rates/short time periods, the time derivative components of the stress–strain relationship dominate.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] In these conditions it can be approximated as a rigid rod capable of sustaining high loads without deforming.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Hence, the dashpot can be considered to be a "short-circuit".
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Conversely, for low stress states/longer time periods, the time derivative components are negligible and the dashpot can be effectively removed from the system – an "open" circuit.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] As a result, only the spring connected in parallel to the dashpot contributes to the total strain in the system.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The Maxwell model can be represented by a purely viscous damper and a purely elastic spring connected in series, as shown in the diagram.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Under this model, if the material is put under a constant strain, the stresses gradually relax.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] When a material is put under a constant stress, the strain has two components.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] First, an elastic component occurs instantaneously, corresponding to the spring, and relaxes immediately upon release of the stress.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The second is a viscous component that grows with time as long as the stress is applied.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The Maxwell model predicts that stress decays exponentially with time, which is accurate for most polymers.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] One limitation of this model is that it does not predict creep accurately.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The Maxwell model for creep or constant-stress conditions postulates that strain increases linearly with time.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] However, polymers for the most part show the strain rate to be decreasing with time.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] This model can be applied to soft solids: thermoplastic polymers in the vicinity of their melting temperature, fresh concrete (neglecting its aging), and numerous metals at a temperature close to their melting point.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The equation introduced here, however, lacks a consistent derivation from more microscopic model and is not observer independent.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The Upper-convected Maxwell model is its sound formulation in terms of the Cauchy stress tensor and constitutes the simplest tensorial constitutive model for viscoelasticity (see e.g. or ).
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The Kelvin–Voigt model, also known as the Voigt model, consists of a Newtonian damper and Hookean elastic spring connected in parallel, as shown in the picture.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] It is used to explain the creep behaviour of polymers.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] This model represents a solid undergoing reversible, viscoelastic strain.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Upon application of a constant stress, the material deforms at a decreasing rate, asymptotically approaching the steady-state strain.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] When the stress is released, the material gradually relaxes to its undeformed state.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] At constant stress (creep), the model is quite realistic as it predicts strain to tend to σ/E as time continues to infinity.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Similar to the Maxwell model, the Kelvin–Voigt model also has limitations.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The model is extremely good with modelling creep in materials, but with regards to relaxation the model is much less accurate.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] This model can be applied to organic polymers, rubber, and wood when the load is not too high.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The standard linear solid model, also referred as the Kelvin or Zener model, consists of two springs and a dashpot.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] This model is referred as Kelvin model by some authors, as Lord Kelvin (William Thomson) observed that the rate of dissipation of energy increases less rapidly than the square of the frequency as predicted by a simple Voigt Model.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Finally, he concluded that simple Voigt Model does not corresponds to reality .
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] However, the standard linear solid model formally proposed by John Henry Poynting and Joseph John Thomson in 1902 .
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] It is the simplest model that describes both the creep and stress relaxation behaviors of a viscoelastic material properly.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Under a constant stress, the modeled material instantaneously deforms to some strain, which is the instantaneous elastic portion of the strain.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] After that it continues to deform and asymptotically approach a steady-state strain, which is the retarded elastic portion of the strain.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Although the standard linear solid model is more accurate than the Maxwell and Kelvin–Voigt models in predicting material responses, mathematically it returns inaccurate results for strain under specific loading conditions.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The Jeffreys model like the Zener model is a three element model.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] It consist of two dashpots and a spring.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] It was proposed in 1929 by Harold Jeffreys to study Earth's mantle.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The Burgers model consists of either two Maxwell components in parallel or a Kelvin–Voigt component, a spring and a dashpot in series.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] This model incorporates viscous flow into the standard linear solid model, giving a linearly increasing asymptote for strain under fixed loading conditions.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The generalized Maxwell model, also known as the Wiechert model, is the most general form of the linear model for viscoelasticity.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] It takes into account that the relaxation does not occur at a single time, but at a distribution of times.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Due to molecular segments of different lengths with shorter ones contributing less than longer ones, there is a varying time distribution.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The Wiechert model shows this by having as many spring–dashpot Maxwell elements as necessary to accurately represent the distribution.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The figure on the right shows the generalised Wiechert model.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Applications: metals and alloys at temperatures lower than one quarter of their absolute melting temperature (expressed in K) and characterizing elastic efficiency.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Non-linear viscoelastic constitutive equations are needed to quantitatively account for phenomena in fluids like differences in normal stresses, shear thinning, and extensional thickening.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Necessarily, the history experienced by the material is needed to account for time-dependent behavior, and is typically included in models as a history kernel **K**.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The second-order fluid is typically considered the simplest nonlinear viscoelastic model, and typically occurs in a narrow region of materials behavior occurring at high strain amplitudes and Deborah number between Newtonian fluids and other more complicated nonlinear viscoelastic fluids.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] $\mathbf {\tau } +\lambda \mathbf {\tau } ^{\triangledown }=2\eta _{0}\mathbf {D}$ where $\mathbf {\tau }$ denotes the stress tensor.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The Oldroyd-B model is an extension of the Upper Convected Maxwell model and is interpreted as a solvent filled with elastic bead and spring dumbbells.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The model is named after its creator James G.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Whilst the model gives good approximations of viscoelastic fluids in shear flow, it has an unphysical singularity in extensional flow, where the dumbbells are infinitely stretched.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] This is, however, specific to idealised flow; in the case of a cross-slot geometry the extensional flow is not ideal, so the stress, although singular, remains integrable, although the stress is infinite in a correspondingly infinitely small region.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] If the solvent viscosity is zero, the Oldroyd-B becomes the Upper Convected Maxwell model.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Wagner model is might be considered as a simplified practical form of the Bernstein–Kearsley–Zapas model.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The model was developed by German rheologist Manfred Wagner.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The *strain damping function* is usually written as: $h(I_{1},I_{2})=m^{*}\exp(-n_{1}{\sqrt {I_{1}-3}})+(1-m^{*})\exp(-n_{2}{\sqrt {I_{2}-3}})$ If the value of the strain hardening function is equal to one, then the deformation is small; if it approaches zero, then the deformations are large.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] In a one-dimensional relaxation test, the material is subjected to a sudden strain that is kept constant over the duration of the test, and the stress is measured over time.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The initial stress is due to the elastic response of the material.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Then, the stress relaxes over time due to the viscous effects in the material.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Typically, either a tensile, compressive, bulk compression, or shear strain is applied.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The resulting stress vs. time data can be fitted with a number of equations, called models.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Only the notation changes depending on the type of strain applied: tensile-compressive relaxation is denoted E , shear is denoted G , bulk is denoted K .
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] where $G_{\infty }$ is the long term modulus once the material is totally relaxed, $\tau _{i}$ are the relaxation times (not to be confused with $\tau _{i}$ in the diagram); the higher their values, the longer it takes for the stress to relax.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The data is fitted with the equation by using a minimization algorithm that adjust the parameters ( $G_{\infty },G_{i},\tau _{i}$ ) to minimize the error between the predicted and data values.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] This form is convenient when the elastic shear modulus $G_{0}$ is obtained from data independent from the relaxation data, and/or for computer implementation, when it is desired to specify the elastic properties separately from the viscous properties, as in Simulia (2010).
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] A creep experiment is usually easier to perform than a relaxation one, so most data is available as (creep) compliance vs. time.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Unfortunately, there is no known closed form for the (creep) compliance in terms of the coefficient of the Prony series.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] So, if one has creep data, it is not easy to get the coefficients of the (relaxation) Prony series, which are needed for example in.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] An expedient way to obtain these coefficients is the following.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] First, fit the creep data with a model that has closed form solutions in both compliance and relaxation; for example the Maxwell-Kelvin model (eq.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Once the parameters of the creep model are known, produce relaxation pseudo-data with the conjugate relaxation model for the same times of the original data.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Finally, fit the pseudo data with the Prony series.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The secondary bonds of a polymer constantly break and reform due to thermal motion.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Application of a stress favors some conformations over others, so the molecules of the polymer gradually "flows" into the favored conformations over time.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Because thermal motion is one factor contributing to the deformation of polymers, viscoelastic properties change with increasing or decreasing temperature.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] In most cases, the creep modulus, defined as the ratio of applied stress to the time-dependent strain, decreases with increasing temperature.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Generally speaking, an increase in temperature correlates to a logarithmic decrease in the time required to impart equal strain under a constant stress.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] In other words, it takes less work to stretch a viscoelastic material an equal distance at a higher temperature than it does at a lower temperature.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] More detailed effect of temperature on the viscoelastic behavior of polymer can be plotted as shown.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] There are mainly five regions (some denoted four, which combines IV and V together) included in the typical polymers.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Extreme cold temperatures can cause viscoelastic materials to change to the glass phase and become brittle.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] For example, exposure of pressure sensitive adhesives to extreme cold (dry ice, freeze spray, etc.) causes them to lose their tack, resulting in debonding.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] When subjected to a step constant stress, viscoelastic materials experience a time-dependent increase in strain.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] This phenomenon is known as viscoelastic creep.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] At time $t_{0}$ , a viscoelastic material is loaded with a constant stress that is maintained for a sufficiently long time period.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The material responds to the stress with a strain that increases until the material ultimately fails, if it is a viscoelastic liquid.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] If, on the other hand, it is a viscoelastic solid, it may or may not fail depending on the applied stress versus the material's ultimate resistance.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] When the stress is maintained for a shorter time period, the material undergoes an initial strain until a time $t_{1}$ , after which the strain immediately decreases (discontinuity) then gradually decreases at times $t>t_{1}$ to a residual strain.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Viscoelastic creep data can be presented by plotting the creep modulus (constant applied stress divided by total strain at a particular time) as a function of time.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Below its critical stress, the viscoelastic creep modulus is independent of stress applied.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] A family of curves describing strain versus time response to various applied stress may be represented by a single viscoelastic creep modulus versus time curve if the applied stresses are below the material's critical stress value.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Viscoelastic creep is important when considering long-term structural design.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Given loading and temperature conditions, designers can choose materials that best suit component lifetimes.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Shear rheometers are based on the idea of putting the material to be measured between two plates, one or both of which move in a shear direction to induce stresses and strains in the material.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The testing can be done at constant strain rate, stress, or in an oscillatory fashion (a form of dynamic mechanical analysis).
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Shear rheometers are typically limited by edge effects where the material may leak out from between the two plates and slipping at the material/plate interface.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Extensional rheometers, also known as extensiometers, measure viscoelastic properties by pulling a viscoelastic fluid, typically uniaxially.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Because this typically makes use of capillary forces and confines the fluid to a narrow geometry, the technique is often limited to fluids with relatively low viscosity like dilute polymer solutions or some molten polymers.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Extensional rheometers are also limited by edge effects at the ends of the extensiometer and pressure differences between inside and outside the capillary.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Despite the apparent limitations mentioned above, extensional rheometry can also be performed on high viscosity fluids.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Although this requires the use of different instruments, these techniques and apparatuses allow for the study of the extensional viscoelastic properties of materials such as polymer melts.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Three of the most common extensional rheometry instruments developed within the last 50 years are the Meissner-type rheometer, the filament stretching rheometer (FiSER), and the Sentmanat Extensional Rheometer (SER).
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The Meissner-type rheometer, developed by Meissner and Hostettler in 1996, uses two sets of counter-rotating rollers to strain a sample uniaxially.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] This method uses a constant sample length throughout the experiment, and supports the sample in between the rollers via an air cushion to eliminate sample sagging effects.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] It does suffer from a few issues – for one, the fluid may slip at the belts which leads to lower strain rates than one would expect.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Additionally, this equipment is challenging to operate and costly to purchase and maintain.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The FiSER rheometer simply contains fluid in between two plates.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] During an experiment, the top plate is held steady and a force is applied to the bottom plate, moving it away from the top one.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The strain rate is measured by the rate of change of the sample radius at its middle.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] It is calculated using the following equation: ${\dot {\epsilon }}=-{\frac {2}{R}}{dR \over dt}$ where R is the mid-radius value and ${\dot {\epsilon }}$ is the strain rate.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The viscosity of the sample is then calculated using the following equation: $\eta ={\frac {F}{\pi R^{2}{\dot {\epsilon }}}}$ where $\eta$ is the sample viscosity, and F is the force applied to the sample to pull it apart.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Much like the Meissner-type rheometer, the SER rheometer uses a set of two rollers to strain a sample at a given rate.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] It then calculates the sample viscosity using the well known equation: $\sigma =\eta {\dot {\epsilon }}$ where $\sigma$ is the stress, $\eta$ is the viscosity and ${\dot {\epsilon }}$ is the strain rate.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The stress in this case is determined via torque transducers present in the instrument.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] The small size of this instrument makes it easy to use and eliminates sample sagging between the rollers.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] A schematic detailing the operation of the SER extensional rheometer can be found on the right.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] These two instruments employ a damping mechanism at various frequencies and time ranges with no appeal to time–temperature superposition.
[src:rheology-materials/viscoelasticity] Using BVS and RUS to study the mechanical properties of materials is important to understanding how a material exhibiting viscoelasticity performs.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In continuum mechanics, **viscosity** is a property of a fluid that quantifies the resistance force acting on fluids when there is relative motion between fluid parcels.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] This resistance force is caused by the stress in fluid parcels, which ideally is directly proportional to the strain rate (the time derivative of strain) that arises when fluid parcels are in relative motion, and the relative speed between the boundary between adjacent fluid parcels is zero.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In liquids, viscosity arises from cohesive molecular forces, while in gases it results from molecular collisions.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Except for the case of superfluidity, there is no fluid with zero viscosity, and thus all fluid flows involve viscous effects to some degree.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] For liquids, it corresponds to the informal concept of *thickness*; for example, syrup has a higher viscosity than water.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Viscosity is defined scientifically as a force multiplied by a time divided by an area.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Thus its SI units are newton-seconds per metre squared, or pascal-seconds.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] For instance, when a viscous fluid is forced through a tube, it flows more quickly near the tube's center line than near its walls.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Some stress (such as a pressure difference between the two ends of the tube) is needed to sustain the flow.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] This is because a force is required to overcome the friction between the layers of the fluid which are in relative motion.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] For a tube with a constant rate of flow, the strength of the compensating force is proportional to the fluid's viscosity.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In general, viscosity depends on a fluid's state, such as its temperature, pressure, and rate of deformation.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] However, the dependence on some of these properties is negligible in certain cases.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] For example, the viscosity of a Newtonian fluid does not vary significantly with the rate of deformation.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Zero viscosity (no resistance to shear stress) is observed only at very low temperatures in superfluids; otherwise, the second law of thermodynamics requires all fluids to have positive viscosity.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] A fluid that has zero viscosity (non-viscous) is called *ideal* or *inviscid*.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] For non-Newtonian fluids' viscosity, there are pseudoplastic, plastic, and dilatant flows that are time-independent, and there are thixotropic and rheopectic flows that are time-dependent.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The word "viscosity" is derived from the Latin **viscum** ("mistletoe").
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] **Viscum** also referred to a viscous glue derived from mistletoe berries.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In materials science and engineering, there is often interest in understanding the forces or stresses involved in the deformation of a material.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] For instance, if the material were a simple spring, the answer would be given by Hooke's law, which says that the force experienced by a spring is proportional to the distance displaced from equilibrium.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Stresses which can be attributed to the deformation of a material from some rest state are called elastic stresses.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In other materials, stresses are present which can be attributed to the deformation rate over time.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] For instance, in a fluid such as water the stresses which arise from shearing the fluid do not depend on the *distance* the fluid has been sheared; rather, they depend on how *quickly* the shearing occurs.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Viscosity is the material property which relates the viscous stresses in a material to the rate of change of a deformation (the strain rate).
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Although it applies to general flows, it is easy to visualize and define in a simple shearing flow, such as a planar Couette flow.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In the Couette flow, a fluid is trapped between two infinitely large plates, one fixed and one in parallel motion at constant speed u (see illustration to the right).
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] If the speed of the top plate is low enough (to avoid turbulence), then in steady state the fluid particles move parallel to it, and their speed varies from 0 at the bottom to u at the top.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Each layer of fluid moves faster than the one just below it, and friction between them gives rise to a force resisting their relative motion.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In particular, the fluid applies on the top plate a force in the direction opposite to its motion, and an equal but opposite force on the bottom plate.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] An external force is therefore required in order to keep the top plate moving at constant speed.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In many fluids, the flow velocity is observed to vary linearly from zero at the bottom to u at the top.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The proportionality factor is the *dynamic viscosity* of the fluid, often simply referred to as the *viscosity*.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] It is denoted by the Greek letter mu (μ).
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] energy per unit volume multiplied by time.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The aforementioned ratio $u/y$ is called the *rate of shear deformation* or *shear velocity*, and is the derivative of the fluid speed in the direction parallel to the normal vector of the plates (see illustrations to the right).
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] where $\tau =F/A$ , and $\partial u/\partial y$ is the local shear velocity.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] This expression is referred to as Newton's law of viscosity.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In shearing flows with planar symmetry, it is what *defines* $\mu$ .
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] It is a special case of the general definition of viscosity (see below), which can be expressed in coordinate-free form.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Use of the Greek letter mu ( $\mu$ ) for the dynamic viscosity (sometimes also called the *absolute viscosity*) is common among mechanical and chemical engineers, as well as mathematicians and physicists.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] However, the Greek letter eta ( $\eta$ ) is also used by chemists, physicists, and the IUPAC.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The viscosity $\mu$ is sometimes also called the *shear viscosity*.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] However, at least one author discourages the use of this terminology, noting that $\mu$ can appear in non-shearing flows in addition to shearing flows.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In fluid dynamics, it is sometimes more appropriate to work in terms of *kinematic viscosity* (sometimes also called the *momentum diffusivity*), defined as the ratio of the dynamic viscosity (μ) over the density of the fluid (ρ).
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] energy per unit mass multiplied by time.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In very general terms, the viscous stresses in a fluid are defined as those resulting from the relative velocity of different fluid particles.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] As such, the viscous stresses must depend on spatial gradients of the flow velocity.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] If the velocity gradients are small, then to a first approximation the viscous stresses depend only on the first derivatives of the velocity.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] where $\mu _{ijk\ell }$ is a viscosity tensor that maps the velocity gradient tensor $\partial v_{k}/\partial r_{\ell }$ onto the viscous stress tensor $\tau _{ij}$ .
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Since the indices in this expression can vary from 1 to 3, there are 81 "viscosity coefficients" $\mu _{ijkl}$ in total.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] and furthermore, it is assumed that no viscous forces may arise when the fluid is undergoing simple rigid-body rotation, thus $\beta =\gamma$ , leaving only two independent parameters.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The most usual decomposition is in terms of the standard (scalar) viscosity $\mu$ and the bulk viscosity $\kappa$ such that $\alpha =\kappa -{\tfrac {2}{3}}\mu$ and $\beta =\gamma =\mu$ .
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] where $\mathbf {\delta }$ is the unit tensor.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] This equation can be thought of as a generalized form of Newton's law of viscosity.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The bulk viscosity (also called volume viscosity) expresses a type of internal friction that resists the shearless compression or expansion of a fluid.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Knowledge of $\kappa$ is frequently not necessary in fluid dynamics problems.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] For example, an incompressible fluid satisfies $\nabla \cdot \mathbf {v} =0$ and so the term containing $\kappa$ drops out.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Moreover, $\kappa$ is often assumed to be negligible for gases since it is 0 in a monatomic ideal gas.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] One situation in which $\kappa$ can be important is the calculation of energy loss in sound and shock waves, described by Stokes' law of sound attenuation, since these phenomena involve rapid expansions and compressions.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The defining equations for viscosity are not fundamental laws of nature, so their usefulness, as well as methods for measuring or calculating the viscosity, must be established using separate means.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] A potential issue is that viscosity depends, in principle, on the full microscopic state of the fluid, which encompasses the positions and momenta of every particle in the system.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Such highly detailed information is typically not available in realistic systems.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] However, under certain conditions most of this information can be shown to be negligible.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In particular, for Newtonian fluids near equilibrium and far from boundaries (bulk state), the viscosity depends only space- and time-dependent macroscopic fields (such as temperature and density) defining local equilibrium.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Nevertheless, viscosity may still carry a non-negligible dependence on several system properties, such as temperature, pressure, and the amplitude and frequency of any external forcing.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Therefore, precision measurements of viscosity are only defined with respect to a specific fluid state.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] To standardize comparisons among experiments and theoretical models, viscosity data is sometimes extrapolated to ideal limiting cases, such as the *zero shear* limit, or (for gases) the *zero density* limit.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] This perspective is implicit in Newton's law of viscosity, $\tau =\mu (\partial u/\partial y)$ , because the shear stress $\tau$ has units equivalent to a momentum flux, i.e., momentum per unit time per unit area.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Thus, $\tau$ can be interpreted as specifying the flow of momentum in the y direction from one fluid layer to the next.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Per Newton's law of viscosity, this momentum flow occurs across a velocity gradient, and the magnitude of the corresponding momentum flux is determined by the viscosity.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The analogy with heat and mass transfer can be made explicit.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Just as heat flows from high temperature to low temperature and mass flows from high density to low density, momentum flows from high velocity to low velocity.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] where $\rho$ is the density, $\mathbf {J}$ and $\mathbf {q}$ are the mass and heat fluxes, and D and $k_{t}$ are the mass diffusivity and thermal conductivity.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The fact that mass, momentum, and energy (heat) transport are among the most relevant processes in continuum mechanics is not a coincidence: these are among the few physical quantities that are conserved at the microscopic level in interparticle collisions.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Thus, rather than being dictated by the fast and complex microscopic interaction timescale, their dynamics occurs on macroscopic timescales, as described by the various equations of transport theory and hydrodynamics.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Newton's law of viscosity is not a fundamental law of nature, but rather a constitutive equation (like Hooke's law, Fick's law, and Ohm's law) which serves to define the viscosity $\mu$ .
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Its form is motivated by experiments which show that for a wide range of fluids, $\mu$ is independent of strain rate.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Gases, water, and many common liquids can be considered Newtonian in ordinary conditions and contexts.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] However, there are many non-Newtonian fluids that significantly deviate from this behavior.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Trouton's ratio is the ratio of extensional viscosity to shear viscosity.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] For a Newtonian fluid, the Trouton ratio is 3.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Shear-thinning liquids are very commonly, but misleadingly, described as thixotropic.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Viscosity may also depend on the fluid's physical state (temperature and pressure) and other, *external*, factors.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] For gases and other compressible fluids, it depends on temperature and varies very slowly with pressure.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The viscosity of some fluids may depend on other factors.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] A magnetorheological fluid, for example, becomes thicker when subjected to a magnetic field, possibly to the point of behaving like a solid.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The viscous forces that arise during fluid flow are distinct from the elastic forces that occur in a solid in response to shear, compression, or extension stresses.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] While in the latter the stress is proportional to the *amount* of shear deformation, in a fluid it is proportional to the *rate* of deformation over time.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] For this reason, James Clerk Maxwell used the term *fugitive elasticity* for fluid viscosity.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] However, many liquids (including water) will briefly react like elastic solids when subjected to sudden stress.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Conversely, many "solids" (even granite) will flow like liquids, albeit very slowly, even under arbitrarily small stress.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Such materials are best described as viscoelastic—that is, possessing both elasticity (reaction to deformation) and viscosity (reaction to rate of deformation).
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Viscoelastic solids may exhibit both shear viscosity and bulk viscosity.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The extensional viscosity is a linear combination of the shear and bulk viscosities that describes the reaction of a solid elastic material to elongation.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] It is widely used for characterizing polymers.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In geology, earth materials that exhibit viscous deformation at least three orders of magnitude greater than their elastic deformation are sometimes called rheids.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Viscosity is measured with various types of viscometers and rheometers.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Close temperature control of the fluid is essential to obtain accurate measurements, particularly in materials like lubricants, whose viscosity can double with a change of only 5 °C.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] A rheometer is used for fluids that cannot be defined by a single value of viscosity and therefore require more parameters to be set and measured than is the case for a viscometer.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] For some fluids, the viscosity is constant over a wide range of shear rates (Newtonian fluids).
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The fluids without a constant viscosity (non-Newtonian fluids) cannot be described by a single number.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Non-Newtonian fluids exhibit a variety of different correlations between shear stress and shear rate.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] One of the most common instruments for measuring kinematic viscosity is the glass capillary viscometer.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In coating industries, viscosity may be measured with a cup in which the efflux time is measured.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] There are several sorts of cup—such as the Zahn cup and the Ford viscosity cup—with the usage of each type varying mainly according to the industry.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Also used in coatings, a *Stormer viscometer* employs load-based rotation to determine viscosity.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The viscosity is reported in Krebs units (KU), which are unique to Stormer viscometers.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Vibrating viscometers can also be used to measure viscosity.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Resonant, or vibrational viscometers work by creating shear waves within the liquid.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In this method, the sensor is submerged in the fluid and is made to resonate at a specific frequency.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] As the surface of the sensor shears through the liquid, energy is lost due to its viscosity.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] This dissipated energy is then measured and converted into a viscosity reading.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] A higher viscosity causes a greater loss of energy.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Volume viscosity can be measured with an acoustic rheometer.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Apparent viscosity is a calculation derived from tests performed on drilling fluid used in oil or gas well development.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] These calculations and tests help engineers develop and maintain the properties of the drilling fluid to the specifications required.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Nanoviscosity (viscosity sensed by nanoprobes) can be measured by fluorescence correlation spectroscopy.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The SI unit of dynamic viscosity is the newton-second per metre squared (N·s/m2), also frequently expressed in the equivalent forms pascal-second (Pa·s), kilogram per meter per second (kg·m−1·s−1) and poiseuille (Pl).
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The CGS unit is the poise (P, or g·cm−1·s−1 = 0.1 Pa·s), named after Jean Léonard Marie Poiseuille.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] It is commonly expressed, particularly in ASTM standards, as *centipoise* (cP).
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The centipoise is convenient because the viscosity of water at 20 °C is about 1 cP, and one centipoise is equal to the SI millipascal second (mPa·s).
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The SI unit of kinematic viscosity is metre squared per second (m2/s), whereas the CGS unit for kinematic viscosity is the **stokes** (St, or cm2·s−1 = 0.0001 m2·s−1), named after Sir George Gabriel Stokes.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In U.S. usage, *stoke* is sometimes used as the singular form.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The submultiple *centistokes* (cSt) is often used instead, 1 cSt = 1 mm2·s−1 = 10−6 m2·s−1.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] 1 cSt is 1 cP divided by 1000 kg/m^3, close to the density of water.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The kinematic viscosity of water at 20 °C is about 1 cSt.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The most frequently used systems of US customary, or Imperial, units are the British Gravitational (BG) and English Engineering (EE).
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In the BG system, dynamic viscosity has units of *pound*-seconds per square foot (lb·s/ft2), and in the EE system it has units of *pound-force*-seconds per square foot (lbf·s/ft2).
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The pound and pound-force are equivalent; the two systems differ only in how force and mass are defined.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Kinematic viscosity has units of square feet per second (ft2/s) in both the BG and EE systems.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Nonstandard units include the reyn (lbf·s/in2), a British unit of dynamic viscosity.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In the automotive industry the viscosity index is used to describe the change of viscosity with temperature.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The reciprocal of viscosity is *fluidity*, usually symbolized by $\phi =1/\mu$ or $F=1/\mu$ , depending on the convention used, measured in *reciprocal poise* (P−1, or cm·s·g−1), sometimes called the *rhe*.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Fluidity is seldom used in engineering practice.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] At one time the petroleum industry relied on measuring kinematic viscosity by means of the Saybolt viscometer, and expressing kinematic viscosity in units of Saybolt universal seconds (SUS).
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Other abbreviations such as SSU (*Saybolt seconds universal*) or SUV (*Saybolt universal viscosity*) are sometimes used.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Kinematic viscosity in centistokes can be converted from SUS according to the arithmetic and the reference table provided in ASTM D 2161.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Momentum transport in gases is mediated by discrete molecular collisions, and in liquids by attractive forces that bind molecules close together.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Because of this, the dynamic viscosities of liquids are typically much larger than those of gases.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In addition, viscosity tends to increase with temperature in gases and decrease with temperature in liquids.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Above the liquid-gas critical point, the liquid and gas phases are replaced by a single supercritical phase.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In this regime, the mechanisms of momentum transport interpolate between liquid-like and gas-like behavior.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] For example, along a supercritical isobar (constant-pressure surface), the kinematic viscosity decreases at low temperature and increases at high temperature, with a minimum in between.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] where $\hbar$ is the Planck constant, $m_{\text{e}}$ is the electron mass, and m is the molecular mass.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In general, however, the viscosity of a system depends in detail on how the molecules constituting the system interact, and there are no simple but correct formulas for it.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The simplest exact expressions are the Green–Kubo relations for the linear shear viscosity or the *transient time correlation function* expressions derived by Evans and Morriss in 1988.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Although these expressions are each exact, calculating the viscosity of a dense fluid using these relations currently requires the use of molecular dynamics computer simulations.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Somewhat more progress can be made for a dilute gas, as elementary assumptions about how gas molecules move and interact lead to a basic understanding of the molecular origins of viscosity.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] More sophisticated treatments can be constructed by systematically coarse-graining the equations of motion of the gas molecules.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] An example of such a treatment is Chapman–Enskog theory, which derives expressions for the viscosity of a dilute gas from the Boltzmann equation.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Consider a dilute gas moving parallel to the x -axis with velocity $u(y)$ that depends only on the y coordinate.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] To simplify the discussion, the gas is assumed to have uniform temperature and density.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Under these assumptions, the x velocity of a molecule passing through $y=0$ is equal to whatever velocity that molecule had when its mean free path $\lambda$ began.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] where $\alpha$ is a numerical constant on the order of 1 .
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Viscosity in gases arises principally from the molecular diffusion that transports momentum between layers of flow.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] where $k_{\text{B}}$ is the Boltzmann constant, m the molecular mass, and $\alpha$ a numerical constant on the order of 1 .
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The quantity $\lambda$ , the mean free path, measures the average distance a molecule travels between collisions.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Even without *a priori* knowledge of $\alpha$ , this expression has nontrivial implications.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In particular, since $\lambda$ is typically inversely proportional to density and increases with temperature, $\mu$ itself should increase with temperature and be independent of density at fixed temperature.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In fact, both of these predictions persist in more sophisticated treatments, and accurately describe experimental observations.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] By contrast, liquid viscosity typically decreases with temperature.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In this case $\lambda$ is independent of temperature, so $\mu \propto T^{1/2}$ .
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] For more complicated molecular models, however, $\lambda$ depends on temperature in a non-trivial way, and simple kinetic arguments as used here are inadequate.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] More fundamentally, the notion of a mean free path becomes imprecise for particles that interact over a finite range, which limits the usefulness of the concept for describing real-world gases.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] A technique developed by Sydney Chapman and David Enskog in the early 1900s allows a more refined calculation of $\mu$ .
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] It is based on the Boltzmann equation, which provides a statistical description of a dilute gas in terms of intermolecular interactions.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The technique allows accurate calculation of $\mu$ for molecular models that are more realistic than rigid elastic spheres, such as those incorporating intermolecular attractions.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Doing so is necessary to reproduce the correct temperature dependence of $\mu$ , which experiments show increases more rapidly than the $T^{1/2}$ trend predicted for rigid elastic spheres.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Indeed, the Chapman–Enskog analysis shows that the predicted temperature dependence can be tuned by varying the parameters in various molecular models.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] A simple example is the Sutherland model, which describes rigid elastic spheres with *weak* mutual attraction.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] This expression is usually named Sutherland's formula.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] If $\mu$ is known from experiments at $T=T_{0}$ and at least one other temperature, then S can be calculated.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Expressions for $\mu$ obtained in this way are qualitatively accurate for a number of simple gases.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Slightly more sophisticated models, such as the Lennard-Jones potential, or the more flexible Mie potential, may provide better agreement with experiments, but only at the cost of a more opaque dependence on temperature.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] A further advantage of these more complex interaction potentials is that they can be used to develop accurate models for a wide variety of properties using the same potential parameters.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In situations where little experimental data is available, this makes it possible to obtain model parameters from fitting to properties such as pure-fluid vapour-liquid equilibria, before using the parameters thus obtained to predict the viscosities of interest with reasonable accuracy.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In some systems, the assumption of spherical symmetry must be abandoned, as is the case for vapors with highly polar molecules like H2O.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In these cases, the Chapman–Enskog analysis is significantly more complicated.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In the kinetic-molecular picture, a non-zero bulk viscosity arises in gases whenever there are non-negligible relaxational timescales governing the exchange of energy between the translational energy of molecules and their internal energy, e.g. rotational and vibrational.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] As such, the bulk viscosity is 0 for a monatomic ideal gas, in which the internal energy of molecules is negligible, but is nonzero for a gas like carbon dioxide, whose molecules possess both rotational and vibrational energy.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In contrast with gases, there is no simple yet accurate picture for the molecular origins of viscosity in liquids.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] At the simplest level of description, the relative motion of adjacent layers in a liquid is opposed primarily by attractive molecular forces acting across the layer boundary.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In this picture, one (correctly) expects viscosity to decrease with increasing temperature.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] This is because increasing temperature increases the random thermal motion of the molecules, which makes it easier for them to overcome their attractive interactions.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Building on this visualization, a simple theory can be constructed in analogy with the discrete structure of a solid: groups of molecules in a liquid are visualized as forming "cages" which surround and enclose single molecules.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] These cages can be occupied or unoccupied, and stronger molecular attraction corresponds to stronger cages.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Due to random thermal motion, a molecule "hops" between cages at a rate which varies inversely with the strength of molecular attractions.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In equilibrium these "hops" are not biased in any direction.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] On the other hand, in order for two adjacent layers to move relative to each other, the "hops" must be biased in the direction of the relative motion.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] where $N_{\text{A}}$ is the Avogadro constant, h is the Planck constant, V is the volume of a mole of liquid, and $T_{\text{b}}$ is the normal boiling point.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] where A and B are constants fit from data.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] On the other hand, several authors express caution with respect to this model.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Errors as large as 30% can be encountered using equation (**1**), compared with fitting equation (**2**) to experimental data.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] More fundamentally, the physical assumptions underlying equation (**1**) have been criticized.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] It has also been argued that the exponential dependence in equation (**1**) does not necessarily describe experimental observations more accurately than simpler, non-exponential expressions.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In light of these shortcomings, the development of a less ad hoc model is a matter of practical interest.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Foregoing simplicity in favor of precision, it is possible to write rigorous expressions for viscosity starting from the fundamental equations of motion for molecules.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] A classic example of this approach is Irving–Kirkwood theory.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] On the other hand, such expressions are given as averages over multiparticle correlation functions and are therefore difficult to apply in practice.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In general, empirically derived expressions (based on existing viscosity measurements) appear to be the only consistently reliable means of calculating viscosity in liquids.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] At the same time equilibrium liquids follow the Arrhenius equation.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The same molecular-kinetic picture of a single component gas can also be applied to a gaseous mixture.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] For instance, in the Chapman–Enskog approach the viscosity $\mu _{\text{mix}}$ of a binary mixture of gases can be written in terms of the individual component viscosities $\mu _{1,2}$ , their respective volume fractions, and the intermolecular interactions.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] As for the single-component gas, the dependence of $\mu _{\text{mix}}$ on the parameters of the intermolecular interactions enters through various collisional integrals which may not be expressible in closed form.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] To obtain usable expressions for $\mu _{\text{mix}}$ which reasonably match experimental data, the collisional integrals may be computed numerically or from correlations.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In some cases, the collision integrals are regarded as fitting parameters, and are fitted directly to experimental data.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] This is a common approach in the development of reference equations for gas-phase viscosities.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] An example of such a procedure is the Sutherland approach for the single-component gas, discussed above.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] For gas mixtures consisting of simple molecules, Revised Enskog Theory has been shown to accurately represent both the density- and temperature dependence of the viscosity over a wide range of conditions.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] As for pure liquids, the viscosity of a blend of liquids is difficult to predict from molecular principles.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] One method is to extend the molecular "cage" theory presented above for a pure liquid.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] This can be done with varying levels of sophistication.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] where $\alpha$ is an empirical parameter, and $x_{1,2}$ and $\mu _{1,2}$ are the respective mole fractions and viscosities of the component liquids.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Since blending is an important process in the lubricating and oil industries, a variety of empirical and proprietary equations exist for predicting the viscosity of a blend.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Depending on the solute and range of concentration, an aqueous electrolyte solution can have either a larger or smaller viscosity compared with pure water at the same temperature and pressure.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] For instance, a 20% saline (sodium chloride) solution has viscosity over 1.5 times that of pure water, whereas a 20% potassium iodide solution has viscosity about 0.91 times that of pure water.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] where $\mu _{0}$ is the viscosity of the solvent, c is the concentration, and A is a positive constant which depends on both solvent and solute properties.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] However, this expression is only valid for very dilute solutions, having c less than 0.1 mol/L.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In particular, a negative value of B is able to account for the decrease in viscosity observed in some solutions.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Estimated values of these constants are shown below for sodium chloride and potassium iodide at temperature 25 °C (mol = mole, L = liter).
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Such suspensions generally exhibit non-Newtonian behavior.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] However, for dilute systems in steady flows, the behavior is Newtonian and expressions for $\mu _{\text{eff}}$ can be derived directly from the particle dynamics.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In a very dilute system, with volume fraction $\phi \lesssim 0.02$ , interactions between the suspended particles can be ignored.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In such a case one can explicitly calculate the flow field around each particle independently, and combine the results to obtain $\mu _{\text{eff}}$ .
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] where $\mu _{0}$ is the viscosity of the suspending liquid.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The linear dependence on $\phi$ is a consequence of neglecting interparticle interactions.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] where the coefficient B may depend on the particle shape (e.g. spheres, rods, disks).
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Experimental determination of the precise value of B is difficult, however: even the prediction $B=5/2$ for spheres has not been conclusively validated, with various experiments finding values in the range $1.5\lesssim B\lesssim 5$ .
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] This deficiency has been attributed to difficulty in controlling experimental conditions.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In denser suspensions, $\mu _{\text{eff}}$ acquires a nonlinear dependence on $\phi$ , which indicates the importance of interparticle interactions.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Various analytical and semi-empirical schemes exist for capturing this regime.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] and the coefficient $B_{1}$ is fit from experimental data or approximated from the microscopic theory.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] However, some authors advise caution in applying such simple formulas since non-Newtonian behavior appears in dense suspensions ( $\phi \gtrsim 0.25$ for spheres), or in suspensions of elongated or flexible particles.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] There is a distinction between a suspension of solid particles, described above, and an emulsion.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The latter is a suspension of tiny droplets, which themselves may exhibit internal circulation.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The presence of internal circulation can decrease the observed effective viscosity, and different theoretical or semi-empirical models must be used.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] where Q is a relevant activation energy, given in terms of molecular parameters; T is temperature; R is the molar gas constant; and A is approximately a constant.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The activation energy Q takes a different value depending on whether the high or low temperature limit is being considered: it changes from a high value *Q*H at low temperatures (in the glassy state) to a low value *Q*L at high temperatures (in the liquid state).
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] For intermediate temperatures, Q varies nontrivially with temperature and the simple Arrhenius form fails.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] where A , B , C , D are all constants, provides a good fit to experimental data over the entire range of temperatures, while at the same time reducing to the correct Arrhenius form in the low and high temperature limits.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] This expression, also known as Duouglas-Doremus-Ojovan model, can be motivated from various theoretical models of amorphous materials at the atomic level.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] A two-exponential equation for the viscosity can be derived within the Dyre shoving model of supercooled liquids, where the Arrhenius energy barrier is identified with the high-frequency shear modulus times a characteristic shoving volume.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Finally, $k_{B}$ denotes the Boltzmann constant.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] In contrast to the viscosity of the fluid itself, which must be positive by the second law of thermodynamics, the eddy viscosity can be negative.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Because viscosity depends continuously on temperature and pressure, it cannot be fully characterized by a finite number of experimental measurements.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Predictive formulas become necessary if experimental values are not available at the temperatures and pressures of interest.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] This capability is important for thermophysical simulations, in which the temperature and pressure of a fluid can vary continuously with space and time.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] For the simplest fluids, such as dilute monatomic gases and their mixtures, *ab initio* quantum mechanical computations can accurately predict viscosity in terms of fundamental atomic constants, i.e., without reference to existing viscosity measurements.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] For the special case of dilute helium, uncertainties in the *ab initio* calculated viscosity are two order of magnitudes smaller than uncertainties in experimental values.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] For slightly more complex fluids and mixtures at moderate densities (i.e. sub-critical densities) Revised Enskog Theory can be used to predict viscosities with some accuracy.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Revised Enskog Theory is predictive in the sense that predictions for viscosity can be obtained using parameters fitted to other, pure-fluid thermodynamic properties or transport properties, thus requiring no *a priori* experimental viscosity measurements.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] For most fluids, high-accuracy, first-principles computations are not feasible.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Rather, theoretical or empirical expressions must be fit to existing viscosity measurements.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] If such an expression is fit to high-fidelity data over a large range of temperatures and pressures, then it is called a "reference correlation" for that fluid.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Reference correlations have been published for many pure fluids; a few examples are water, carbon dioxide, ammonia, benzene, and xenon.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Many of these cover temperature and pressure ranges that encompass gas, liquid, and supercritical phases.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Thermophysical modeling software often relies on reference correlations for predicting viscosity at user-specified temperature and pressure.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Examples are REFPROP (proprietary) and CoolProp (open-source).
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] Viscosity can also be computed using formulas that express it in terms of the statistics of individual particle trajectories.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] These formulas include the Green–Kubo relations for the linear shear viscosity and the *transient time correlation function* expressions derived by Evans and Morriss in 1988.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The advantage of these expressions is that they are formally exact and valid for general systems.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] The disadvantage is that they require detailed knowledge of particle trajectories, available only in computationally expensive simulations such as molecular dynamics.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p01] An accurate model for interparticle interactions is also required, which may be difficult to obtain for complex molecules.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p02] Observed values of viscosity vary over several orders of magnitude, even for common substances (see the order of magnitude table below).
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p02] For instance, a 70% sucrose (sugar) solution has a viscosity over 400 times that of water, and 26,000 times that of air.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p02] More dramatically, pitch has been estimated to have a viscosity 230 billion times that of water.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p02] The dynamic viscosity $\mu$ of water is about 0.89 mPa·s at room temperature (25 °C).
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p02] As a function of temperature in kelvins, the viscosity can be estimated using the semi-empirical Vogel-Fulcher-Tammann equation: $\mu =Ae^{\frac {B}{T-C}}$ where *A* = 0.02939 mPa·s, *B* = 507.88 K, and *C* = 149.3 K.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p02] Experimentally determined values of the viscosity are also given in the table below.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p02] The values at 20 °C are a useful reference: there, the dynamic viscosity is about 1 cP and the kinematic viscosity is about 1 cSt.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p02] Under standard atmospheric conditions (25 °C and pressure of 1 bar), the dynamic viscosity of air is 18.5 μPa·s, roughly 50 times smaller than the viscosity of water at the same temperature.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p02] Except at very high pressure, the viscosity of air depends mostly on the temperature.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p02] which is accurate in the range −20 °C to 400 °C.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p02] For this formula to be valid, the temperature must be given in kelvins; $\eta _{\text{air}}$ then corresponds to the viscosity in Pa·s.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p02] The following table illustrates the range of viscosity values observed in common substances.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p02] Unless otherwise noted, a temperature of 25 °C and a pressure of 1 atmosphere are assumed.
[src:rheology-materials/viscosity-p02] The values listed are representative estimates only, as they do not account for measurement uncertainties, variability in material definitions, or non-Newtonian behavior.
